WEBVTT

1
00:02:40.655 --> 00:02:41.700
Ned Lewis.

2
00:02:43.136 --> 00:02:44.136
Who?

3
00:02:45.182 --> 00:02:46.531
My bank?

4
00:02:47.836 --> 00:02:50.012
A guy from my bank?

5
00:02:50.056 --> 00:02:52.624
My bank sent some guy over.

6
00:02:52.667 --> 00:02:55.366
God, I can't be that far overdrawn.

7
00:02:55.409 --> 00:02:58.064
All right. Yeah, tell
him I'll be right down.

8
00:03:06.159 --> 00:03:07.639
- Ned Lewis?
- Yeah.


9
00:03:07.682 --> 00:03:09.902
Lenny Brown. Can we talk in your office?

10
00:03:09.945 --> 00:03:12.470
So you're from
Manufacturer's Hanover Trust?


11
00:03:12.513 --> 00:03:13.993
No, where did you get that idea, Ned?

12
00:03:14.036 --> 00:03:15.734
I thought you told Johnny...

13
00:03:15.777 --> 00:03:17.726
I told Johnny I was from
Equity Appreciation Associates.


14
00:03:17.736 --> 00:03:20.478
Maybe he got the idea that was
a bank, but I'm no banker, Ned.


15
00:03:20.521 --> 00:03:24.177
I want to talk to you about saving
$250,000 on your income tax this year.


16
00:03:24.221 --> 00:03:25.483
Is this a joke?

17
00:03:25.526 --> 00:03:26.919
Cattle feed is highly leveraged.

18
00:03:26.962 --> 00:03:29.008
The write-off this year is 4-to-1.

19
00:03:29.051 --> 00:03:31.271
It's all been blue sky
and it's perfectly kosher.


20
00:03:31.315 --> 00:03:35.493
Look, I made $28,200 last
year. I'm just a working stiff.


21
00:03:35.536 --> 00:03:37.049
No, I was talking about the interest income

22
00:03:37.059 --> 00:03:38.529
from that money your father gave you.

23
00:03:38.539 --> 00:03:40.846
What money? My father
didn't give me any money.


24
00:03:40.889 --> 00:03:43.196
Your father is Edward
Lewis at Dreyfus, right?


25
00:03:43.240 --> 00:03:45.067
Where'd you get an idea like that?

26
00:03:45.111 --> 00:03:47.244
My father's a professor at CUNY.

27
00:03:47.287 --> 00:03:49.236
This girl you went out with,
she works with my wife.


28
00:03:49.246 --> 00:03:51.422
- She mentioned you.
- What girl?


29
00:03:51.465 --> 00:03:53.501
She said your father was
some famous guy about money


30
00:03:53.511 --> 00:03:54.860
and I put two and two together.

31
00:03:54.903 --> 00:03:57.210
Teaches economics.
Hardly famous.


32
00:03:57.254 --> 00:04:00.082
You don't know anybody who could use

33
00:04:00.126 --> 00:04:02.389
a $250,000 tax shelter, do you?

34
00:04:02.433 --> 00:04:04.086
Not personally.

35
00:04:04.130 --> 00:04:05.479
I'm such a schmuck.

36
00:04:05.523 --> 00:04:07.046
Sorry.
Wrong me, I guess.


37
00:04:07.089 --> 00:04:09.135
Thanks for not jerking me around, you know.

38
00:04:09.179 --> 00:04:10.876
I leave a piece of
my soul on the floor

39
00:04:10.919 --> 00:04:12.346
every time I do this song and dance.

40
00:04:12.356 --> 00:04:13.444
No problem.

41
00:04:13.487 --> 00:04:14.836
Go out like a battleship,

42
00:04:14.880 --> 00:04:17.491
come back like a raft.
Thanks.


43
00:04:17.535 --> 00:04:20.277
You've really got a 4-to-1 write-off?

44
00:04:20.320 --> 00:04:22.104
That's what they tell me.

45
00:04:22.148 --> 00:04:24.194
Hey...

46
00:04:24.237 --> 00:04:26.544
Can I buy you lunch
as my way of apologizing?


47
00:04:26.587 --> 00:04:27.980
No, that's okay, really.

48
00:04:28.023 --> 00:04:29.982
Please, I'd like the company.

49
00:04:31.244 --> 00:04:32.898
Yeah? Okay.

50
00:04:32.941 --> 00:04:34.639
It's just so funny.
I got the...


51
00:04:34.682 --> 00:04:36.380
I could never be in sales.

52
00:04:36.423 --> 00:04:38.730
It hurts your feelings too much
when you get turned down.


53
00:04:38.773 --> 00:04:40.635
Sometimes I get discouraged,
maybe even a little depressed,


54
00:04:40.645 --> 00:04:42.255
but you got to shrug it off.

55
00:04:42.299 --> 00:04:43.899
I could let it get to me,
go around fractured,


56
00:04:43.909 --> 00:04:45.780
But thank God I got somebody at home.

57
00:04:45.824 --> 00:04:47.391
She won't ask,
"Did you make the sale?"


58
00:04:47.434 --> 00:04:49.958
She'll just give a hug and
a kiss and I'm whole again.


59
00:04:50.002 --> 00:04:51.133
Len, you're a lucky man.

60
00:04:51.177 --> 00:04:52.177
Ah, I know that.

61
00:04:53.788 --> 00:04:56.269
I keep reminding myself.
You got a wife or anything?


62
00:04:56.313 --> 00:04:58.010
No, nothing.

63
00:04:58.053 --> 00:04:59.751
You'd have to take second best anyhow.

64
00:04:59.794 --> 00:05:01.786
If you saw Linda and me, you
know, at a restaurant like this


65
00:05:01.796 --> 00:05:03.885
you'd say,
"There's a mismatch."


66
00:05:03.929 --> 00:05:05.713
I've seen it in people's eyes.

67
00:05:05.757 --> 00:05:08.499
"How did a guy like that get a
girl like her? He must be rich."


68
00:05:08.542 --> 00:05:11.241
Not that I'm not trying.

69
00:05:11.284 --> 00:05:12.894
You know, here's the funny part.

70
00:05:12.938 --> 00:05:14.940
Money doesn't mean a thing to Linda.

71
00:05:14.983 --> 00:05:17.062
It's nice to hear somebody
talk about his wife that way.


72
00:05:17.072 --> 00:05:19.717
You know, most of the guys I know,
they put their wives down all the time.


73
00:05:19.727 --> 00:05:20.815
Would you like to meet her?

74
00:05:20.859 --> 00:05:22.556
Yeah, sure.
Sometime.


75
00:05:22.600 --> 00:05:25.211
You could come to dinner.
Here's my card.


76
00:05:27.344 --> 00:05:29.520
- So, what do you think? Tonight?
- Tonight?


77
00:05:29.563 --> 00:05:30.859
- Yeah, dinner at our place.
- You're sure?


78
00:05:30.869 --> 00:05:33.175
You don't want to check with your wife?

79
00:05:33.219 --> 00:05:35.777
I'll tell her I met a guy, invited him to
dinner. She'll say, "Great, no sweat."


80
00:05:35.787 --> 00:05:37.169
You'll wonder how a schmuck like me

81
00:05:37.179 --> 00:05:38.964
Wound up with a beauty like Linda.

82
00:05:40.270 --> 00:05:41.967
Funny way to start a friendship,

83
00:05:42.010 --> 00:05:43.838
me thinking you were someone else, huh?

84
00:05:43.882 --> 00:05:45.569
Well, back to the salt mines.
Got to catch a cab.


85
00:05:45.579 --> 00:05:46.841
Thanks for lunch.

86
00:05:46.885 --> 00:05:47.581
Anytime.
See you tonight, okay?


87
00:05:47.625 --> 00:05:49.017
- Right.
- Bye-bye.


88
00:06:06.774 --> 00:06:08.254
Linda?

89
00:06:10.300 --> 00:06:11.823
Linda, Ned is here.

90
00:06:17.263 --> 00:06:20.179
Welcome to CasaBrown.
Let me take your coat.


91
00:06:20.222 --> 00:06:22.094
Linda, Ned is here.

92
00:06:22.137 --> 00:06:23.835
It's still raining, huh?

93
00:06:23.878 --> 00:06:26.881
Linda?
Oh, Linda.


94
00:06:26.925 --> 00:06:28.482
This is Ned Lewis of the Financial Journal.

95
00:06:28.492 --> 00:06:29.580
Hello, Ned.

96
00:06:29.623 --> 00:06:31.103
Pleased to meet you.

97
00:06:31.146 --> 00:06:33.410
- Was I right or was I right?
- You were right.


98
00:06:33.453 --> 00:06:35.760
Is she, like, the most
beautiful girl you ever met?


99
00:06:35.803 --> 00:06:37.501
No question.

100
00:06:37.544 --> 00:06:39.503
He loves me.

101
00:06:39.546 --> 00:06:41.026
What do you do?

102
00:06:41.069 --> 00:06:43.071
I'm a paralegal at a corporate law firm.

103
00:06:43.115 --> 00:06:44.116
Sounds interesting.

104
00:06:44.159 --> 00:06:46.031
Dull as dishwater.

105
00:06:46.074 --> 00:06:47.902
Lenny's the talent in the family.

106
00:06:47.946 --> 00:06:50.296
She's being modest.
You should see her dance.


107
00:06:50.340 --> 00:06:51.689
You dance?

108
00:06:51.732 --> 00:06:54.431
Does she dance?
She dances like a dream.


109
00:06:54.474 --> 00:06:56.945
I wanted to be a ballerina. I
guess most little girls do, but...


110
00:06:56.955 --> 00:06:58.086
No buts about it.

111
00:06:58.130 --> 00:06:59.087
You'll have whatever you want.

112
00:06:59.131 --> 00:07:00.437
That's a promise.

113
00:07:01.655 --> 00:07:04.136
I'm happy just taking classes.

114
00:07:04.179 --> 00:07:06.747
Uh, I'm a little too old
to be a professional.


115
00:07:06.791 --> 00:07:09.671
Now, I bet you never heard a beautiful
girl admit to that, huh, Ned? Huh?


116
00:07:11.404 --> 00:07:13.885
So, how long have you been with Equity?

117
00:07:13.928 --> 00:07:16.888
Oh, Equity Appreciation Associates.

118
00:07:16.931 --> 00:07:19.760
Well, I'm not really with them.

119
00:07:19.804 --> 00:07:22.850
I'm freelancing. I do PR work,
some favors here and there.


120
00:07:22.894 --> 00:07:25.234
The problem with EAA is they
won't give me any decent leads.


121
00:07:25.244 --> 00:07:27.444
That's how I wound up barking
up your tree this morning.


122
00:07:28.378 --> 00:07:29.988
Lenny told me about the mistake.

123
00:07:30.031 --> 00:07:32.120
I didn't know whether to laugh or cry.

124
00:07:32.164 --> 00:07:33.590
He was sort of counting on that sale...

125
00:07:33.600 --> 00:07:35.341
- Honey.
- ...to break into the business.


126
00:07:35.385 --> 00:07:36.854
That thing doesn't mean anything to Ned.

127
00:07:36.864 --> 00:07:38.039
Does it?

128
00:07:38.083 --> 00:07:39.780
- What kind of thing?
- Hustling for money.


129
00:07:39.824 --> 00:07:41.468
You're above all that, writing
for a big paper and everything.


130
00:07:41.478 --> 00:07:43.697
I worry about money, Lenny,
just like everybody else.


131
00:07:43.741 --> 00:07:45.133
But you got some backstops.

132
00:07:45.177 --> 00:07:47.527
You start falling down that well...

133
00:07:47.571 --> 00:07:50.138
You got some slats across
to catch yourself, all right?


134
00:07:50.182 --> 00:07:52.271
I saw a funny
thing on the bus today.

135
00:07:52.314 --> 00:07:54.142
A man got on with a French horn...

136
00:07:54.186 --> 00:07:55.666
You got your professor father.

137
00:07:55.709 --> 00:07:57.407
You got an education.

138
00:07:57.450 --> 00:07:59.713
You got the Financial Journal.
You can't fall too far.


139
00:07:59.757 --> 00:08:03.108
The bus driver wanted the man with
the French horn to pay an extra fare


140
00:08:03.151 --> 00:08:05.066
because the French horn
took up so much room.


141
00:08:05.110 --> 00:08:07.373
My old man's an ex-printer on disability.

142
00:08:07.417 --> 00:08:10.028
My mother is a secretary for the
Ladies Garment Workers Union.


143
00:08:10.071 --> 00:08:11.943
So the man with the French horn,

144
00:08:11.986 --> 00:08:13.684
he said that he would play a concert

145
00:08:13.727 --> 00:08:15.555
for everybody instead, and he did...

146
00:08:15.599 --> 00:08:17.557
I got a high school education!

147
00:08:17.601 --> 00:08:19.994
...all the way
across 86th Street.


148
00:08:20.038 --> 00:08:21.735
It was beautiful.
I cried.


149
00:08:29.351 --> 00:08:31.005
I drank too much wine.

150
00:08:33.007 --> 00:08:35.488
You only had two glasses.

151
00:08:35.532 --> 00:08:36.881
You're just tired.

152
00:08:38.186 --> 00:08:39.884
Work too hard.

153
00:08:42.016 --> 00:08:43.061
Yeah.

154
00:08:45.629 --> 00:08:47.195
I'm a little tired, I guess.

155
00:08:48.545 --> 00:08:50.416
What do you think of Ned?

156
00:08:50.460 --> 00:08:52.070
He seems very nice.

157
00:08:54.638 --> 00:08:56.107
I wonder if we
could get a little blurb

158
00:08:56.117 --> 00:08:58.990
in the Journal about Manny's Pizza Parlor.

159
00:08:59.033 --> 00:09:01.819
You know, how he started.

160
00:09:01.862 --> 00:09:03.777
It's a great success story.

161
00:09:03.821 --> 00:09:05.866
Lenny, you can't ask him.

162
00:09:05.910 --> 00:09:07.694
It's the Financial Journal.

163
00:09:07.738 --> 00:09:09.609
It'd be worth a grand.

164
00:09:15.049 --> 00:09:17.302
My heart falls in on itself
when you look at me like that.


165
00:09:17.312 --> 00:09:18.488
Lenny...

166
00:09:19.880 --> 00:09:21.186
I love you.

167
00:09:21.229 --> 00:09:24.015
It hurts me to see you belittle yourself.

168
00:09:26.234 --> 00:09:27.234
I know.

169
00:09:28.715 --> 00:09:29.847
You're right.

170
00:09:31.675 --> 00:09:35.026
Sometimes I think I can't cut it.

171
00:09:35.069 --> 00:09:38.159
No matter how hard I try,
like, I'm in quicksand.


172
00:09:38.203 --> 00:09:39.944
And the more I struggle...

173
00:09:41.902 --> 00:09:43.425
The deeper I sink.

174
00:09:43.469 --> 00:09:44.905
It'll be all right.

175
00:09:47.734 --> 00:09:48.996
Don't ever leave me.

176
00:09:49.040 --> 00:09:50.998
Silly, I'd never leave you.

177
00:09:51.042 --> 00:09:52.260
I know things look bleak.

178
00:09:52.304 --> 00:09:54.219
Things are not bleak, Lenny.

179
00:09:54.262 --> 00:09:57.222
I'm very happy.
Don't you know that?


180
00:09:59.441 --> 00:10:01.487
Just stick with me...

181
00:10:01.531 --> 00:10:03.315
Please.

182
00:10:03.358 --> 00:10:04.925
Till I fall off the Earth.

183
00:10:08.668 --> 00:10:10.409
Come to bed.

184
00:10:10.452 --> 00:10:11.671
Make love to me.

185
00:10:23.944 --> 00:10:25.293
Good morning.
Hallis-Richardson.


186
00:10:27.121 --> 00:10:29.384
May I say who's calling?

187
00:10:29.428 --> 00:10:30.472
One moment, please.

188
00:10:32.518 --> 00:10:34.085
Mr. Rogers on 7.

189
00:10:35.521 --> 00:10:37.088
Good morning.
Hallis-Richardson.


190
00:10:37.131 --> 00:10:38.176
Shit.

191
00:10:38.219 --> 00:10:39.264
Please hold.

192
00:10:40.961 --> 00:10:42.267
Reception.

193
00:10:43.616 --> 00:10:44.791
Yes, Mr. Hallis.

194
00:10:48.403 --> 00:10:50.318
They're ready for you,
Mr. Brown.


195
00:10:50.362 --> 00:10:51.581
Thank you.

196
00:10:55.628 --> 00:10:58.544
- Ah. Mr. Brown.
- Call me Lenny.


197
00:10:59.850 --> 00:11:01.232
Gentlemen, Mr. 
Brown has applied to be

198
00:11:01.242 --> 00:11:04.637
our sales rep on the Connecticut project.

199
00:11:04.681 --> 00:11:07.379
Tell us a little bit
about yourself, Mr. Brown.


200
00:11:10.600 --> 00:11:13.341
Gentlemen, I won't bore you
with the reading of my resume,


201
00:11:13.385 --> 00:11:15.387
some of which is even true.

202
00:11:15.430 --> 00:11:17.215
I assume you all know how to read.

203
00:11:17.258 --> 00:11:19.478
Besides, we're born again
with each new project.


204
00:11:19.521 --> 00:11:22.394
And all your past successes and
dean's list semesters don't cut much ice


205
00:11:22.437 --> 00:11:23.646
when it comes to the big question:

206
00:11:23.656 --> 00:11:25.005
will it sell?

207
00:11:25.049 --> 00:11:27.355
Then tell us, Mr. Brown.
Will it sell?


208
00:11:27.399 --> 00:11:29.270
Sure, oh, yeah, it'll sell.

209
00:11:29.314 --> 00:11:31.359
Over the life of the partnership,

210
00:11:31.403 --> 00:11:34.624
I guess everyone will enjoy
some small tax benefits,


211
00:11:34.667 --> 00:11:37.975
realize a nice, safe, though
modest return on their investment.


212
00:11:38.018 --> 00:11:39.454
You don't need me for that.

213
00:11:39.498 --> 00:11:41.152
But will it soar?

214
00:11:41.195 --> 00:11:42.806
That's another question.

215
00:11:42.849 --> 00:11:44.808
And I'm afraid the answer is no.

216
00:11:44.851 --> 00:11:46.843
When your aunt Peggy and
the cousins get off the train,


217
00:11:46.853 --> 00:11:48.986
you're not gonna rush
them over to this mall,


218
00:11:49.029 --> 00:11:52.163
Because you don't really identify
with it. Sure, it's quaint, I guess.


219
00:11:52.206 --> 00:11:53.643
But it's also boring.

220
00:11:53.686 --> 00:11:56.254
People struggle against
smallness all their lives.


221
00:11:56.297 --> 00:11:59.387
Let them identify with something big.

222
00:11:59.431 --> 00:12:02.782
You got a duplex theater here.
Show "A" or show "B." That's it.


223
00:12:02.826 --> 00:12:05.655
